      "step_index": 2,
      "step_type": "reasoning",
      "content": "### 2) REASON (SAR) \u2014 why features affect CYP2D6 inhibition\n- **Protonatable tertiary amine \u2192 increases inhibition likelihood.** CYP2D6 inhibition often correlates with a **cationic nitrogen** that can form an ionic interaction with Asp301 and orient the molecule in the active site.\n- **Lack of aromatic/lipophilic ring \u2192 reduces inhibition potency.** Without an aromatic hydrophobe, binding affinity to CYP2D6\u2019s hydrophobic regions is typically weaker, often shifting compounds from strong inhibitors to weak/non-inhibitors.\n- **Multiple oxygens (esters + alcohols) \u2192 may further reduce affinity.** Added polarity/H-bonding can increase solvation and reduce partitioning into the largely hydrophobic active site (though this is not absolute).",
